So let's first row reduce the matrix matrix and see what we get. First, we can subtract the first row multiplied by 2 from the third row to get a 0 in the top-right corner. Then we can subtract 3 times the first row from the second row to get a 0 in the bottom-left corner. <Now that we have the upper triangular matrix, we can use back-substitution to find the solution.</think><answer>
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 3/2 & -1/2 \\ 0 & 4 & 5 \\ 0 & -9 & 1 \end{pmatrix} \mathbf{v} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 27/4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \\
\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 3/2 & -1/2 \\ 0 & 1 & 5/4 \\ 0 & 0 & 11/4 \end{pmatrix} \mathbf{v} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 27/4 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \\
\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & -1 \\ 0 & 1 & 5/4 \\ 0 & 0 & 11/4 \end{pmatrix} \mathbf{v} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} \\
\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} \mathbf{v} &= \begin{pmatrix} 3/2 \\ 1/11 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
So the solution is $\mathbf{v} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 3/2 \\ 1/11 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}}.$</answer>

problem:
In $\triangle ABC$, what is the value of $x + y$? [asy]
import olympiad;
size(7cm);

pair a = dir(76);
pair b = (-1, 0);
pair c = (1, 0);
pair o = (0, 0);

draw(a--b--c--cycle);
draw(a--o);

label("$A$", a, N); label("$B$", b, SW); label("$C$", c, SE);
label("$104^\circ$", o, 1.8 * NW + 0.4 * E);
label("$x^\circ$", b, 3 * E + NE + NE);
label("$y^\circ$", c, 2 * W + 2 * NW);

add(pathticks(b--o, s=3));
add(pathticks(c--o, s=3));
add(pathticks(a--o, s=3));

[/asy]

solution:
Since $\triangle BDA$ is isosceles, $\angle BAD = \angle ABD = x^\circ$.
Since $\triangle CDA$ is isosceles, $\angle CAD = \angle ACD = y^\circ$. [asy]
import olympiad;
size(7cm);

pair a = dir(76);
pair b = (-1, 0);
pair c = (1, 0);
pair o = (0, 0);

draw(a--b--c--cycle);
draw(a--o);

label("$A$", a, N); label("$B$", b, SW); label("$C$", c, SE); label("$D$", o, S);
label("$104^\circ$", o, 1.8 * NW + 0.4 * E);
label("$x^\circ$", b, 3 * E + NE + NE);
label("$y^\circ$", c, 2 * W + 2 * NW);

add(pathticks(b--o, s=3));
add(pathticks(c--o, s=3));
add(pathticks(a--o, s=3));

label("$x^\circ$", a, 3 * S + 2 * SW + W); label("$y^\circ$", a, 3 * S + SE);

[/asy] Therefore, $\angle BAC = (x + y)^\circ$.

Since the sum of the angles in $\triangle ABC$ is $180^\circ$, we have \begin{align*}
x + y + (x + y) &= 180\\
2x + 2y &= 180\\
x + y &= 90.
\end{align*}Therefore, $x + y = \boxed{90}$.

